04480nam a22006855i 9781477317051DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212018txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018001199  a97814773170517 a10.7560/3170442doi  a(DE-B1597)586722  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aGN648b.W95 2018 4aGN648 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.09621 aWynn, L. L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLove, Sex, and Desire in Modern Egypt :bNavigating the Margins of Respectability /cL. L. Wynn. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Foreigners Like Things Looking Old and Dark, Not Shiny -- t2. Mimesis, Kinship, Gift, and Other Things That Bind Us in Love and Desire -- t3. “Why Can’t You Study Respectable Women?” -- t4. Mimesis, Genre, Gender, and Sexuality in Middle East Tourism -- t5. Demimonde: Belly Dancers, Extramarital Affairs, and the Respectability of Women -- t6. Gift, Prostitute: Money and Intimacy -- t7. “Honor Killing”: On Anthropological Writing in an International Political Economy of Representations -- t8. Kinship, Honor, and Shame -- t9. Love, Revolution, and Intimate Violence -- tEpilogue. Fifteen Years Later -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCairo is a city obsessed with honor and respectability—and love affairs. Sara, a working-class woman, has an affair with a married man and becomes pregnant, only to be abandoned by him; Ayah and Zeid, a respectably engaged couple, argue over whether Ayah’s friend is a prostitute or a virgin; Malak, a European belly dancer who sometimes gets paid for sex, wants to be loved by a man who won’t treat her like a whore just because she’s a dancer; and Alia, a Christian banker who left her abusive husband, is the mistress of a wealthy Muslim man, Haroun, who encourages business by hosting risqué parties for other men and their mistresses. Set in transnational Cairo over two decades, Love, Sex, and Desire in Modern Egypt is an ethnography that explores female respectability, male honor, and Western theories and fantasies about Arab society. L. L. Wynn uses stories of love affairs to interrogate three areas of classic anthropological theory: mimesis, kinship, and gift. She develops a broad picture of how individuals love and desire within a cultural and political system that structures the possibilities of, and penalties for, going against sexual and gender norms. Wynn demonstrates that love is at once a moral horizon, an attribute that “naturally” inheres in particular social relations, a social phenomenon strengthened through cultural concepts of gift and kinship, and an emotion deeply felt and desired by individuals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aEthnologyzEgypt. 0aMan-woman relationshipszEgypty21st century. 0aSex rolezEgypty21st century. 0aWomenxSexual behaviorzEgypty21st century. 0aWomenzEgyptxSocial conditionsy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31704440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477317051423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477317051/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK